dom-idbcursor-advance.name: advance
dom-idbcursor-advance.summary: The advance() method of the IDBCursor interface sets the number of times a cursor should move its position forward.
dom-idbcursor-advance.title: IDBCursor.advance()

dom-idbcursor-continue.name: continue
dom-idbcursor-continue.summary: The continue() method of the IDBCursor interface advances the cursor to the next position along its direction, to the item whose key matches the optional key parameter. If no key is specified, the cursor advances to the immediate next position, based on its direction.
dom-idbcursor-continue.title: IDBCursor.continue()

dom-idbcursor-continueprimarykey.name: continuePrimaryKey
dom-idbcursor-continueprimarykey.summary: The continuePrimaryKey() method of the IDBCursor interface advances the cursor to the to the item whose key matches the key parameter as well as whose primary key matches the primary key parameter.
dom-idbcursor-continueprimarykey.title: IDBCursor.continuePrimaryKey()

dom-idbcursor-delete.name: delete
dom-idbcursor-delete.summary: The delete() method of the IDBCursor interface returns an IDBRequest object, and, in a separate thread, deletes the record at the cursor's position, without changing the cursor's position. Once the record is deleted, the cursor's value is set to null.
dom-idbcursor-delete.title: IDBCursor.delete()

dom-idbcursor-direction.name: direction
dom-idbcursor-direction.summary: A string (defined by the IDBCursorDirection enum) indicating the direction in which the cursor is traversing the data. Possible values are:
dom-idbcursor-direction.title: IDBCursor.direction

dom-idbcursor-primarykey.name: primaryKey
dom-idbcursor-primarykey.summary: A value of any data type.
dom-idbcursor-primarykey.title: IDBCursor.primaryKey

dom-idbcursor-request.name: request
dom-idbcursor-request.summary: The request read-only property of the IDBCursor interface returns the IDBRequest used to obtain the cursor.
dom-idbcursor-request.title: IDBCursor.request

dom-idbcursor-source.name: source
dom-idbcursor-source.summary: The IDBObjectStore or IDBIndex that the cursor is iterating over.
dom-idbcursor-source.title: IDBCursor.source

dom-idbcursor-update.name: update
dom-idbcursor-update.summary: The update() method of the IDBCursor interface returns an IDBRequest object, and, in a separate thread, updates the value at the current position of the cursor in the object store. If the cursor points to a record that has just been deleted, a new record is created.
dom-idbcursor-update.title: IDBCursor.update()

cursor-interface.name: IDBCursor
cursor-interface.summary: The IDBCursor interface of the IndexedDB API represents a cursor for traversing or iterating over multiple records in a database.
cursor-interface.title: IDBCursor

database-interface.name: value
database-interface.summary: The value of the current cursor.
database-interface.title: IDBCursorWithValue.value

database-interface.name: IDBDatabase
database-interface.summary: The IDBDatabase interface of the IndexedDB API provides a connection to a database; you can use an IDBDatabase object to open a transaction on your database then create, manipulate, and delete objects (data) in that database. The interface provides the only way to get and manage versions of the database.
database-interface.title: IDBDatabase

idbcursorwithvalue.name: IDBCursorWithValue
idbcursorwithvalue.summary: The IDBCursorWithValue interface of the IndexedDB API represents a cursor for traversing or iterating over multiple records in a database. It is the same as the IDBCursor, except that it includes the value property.
idbcursorwithvalue.title: IDBCursorWithValue

dom-idbdatabase-close.name: close
dom-idbdatabase-close.summary: The connection is not actually closed until all transactions created using this connection are complete. No new transactions can be created for this connection once this method is called. Methods that create transactions throw an exception if a closing operation is pending.
dom-idbdatabase-close.title: IDBDatabase.close()

dom-idbdatabase-createobjectstore.name: createObjectStore
dom-idbdatabase-createobjectstore.summary: The method takes the name of the store as well as a parameter object that lets you define important optional properties. You can use the property to uniquely identify individual objects in the store. As the property is an identifier, it should be unique to every object, and every object should have that property.
dom-idbdatabase-createobjectstore.title: IDBDatabase.createObjectStore()

dom-idbdatabase-deleteobjectstore.name: deleteObjectStore
dom-idbdatabase-deleteobjectstore.summary: As with IDBDatabase.createObjectStore, this method can be called only within a versionchange transaction.
dom-idbdatabase-deleteobjectstore.title: IDBDatabase.deleteObjectStore()

dom-idbdatabase-name.name: name
dom-idbdatabase-name.summary: A DOMString containing the name of the connected database.
dom-idbdatabase-name.title: IDBDatabase.name

dom-idbdatabase-objectstorenames.name: objectStoreNames
dom-idbdatabase-objectstorenames.summary: A DOMStringList containing a list of the names of the object stores currently in the connected database.
dom-idbdatabase-objectstorenames.title: IDBDatabase.objectStoreNames

dom-idbdatabase-onabort.name: onabort
dom-idbdatabase-onabort.summary: The onabort event handler of the IDBDatabase interface handles the abort event, fired when a transaction is aborted and bubbles up to the connection object.
dom-idbdatabase-onabort.title: IDBDatabase.onabort

dom-idbdatabase-onclose.name: onclose
dom-idbdatabase-onclose.summary: A function which is called when the close event is fired.
dom-idbdatabase-onclose.title: IDBDatabase.onclose

dom-idbdatabase-onerror.name: onerror
dom-idbdatabase-onerror.summary: The onerror event handler of the IDBDatabase interface handles the error event, fired when a request returns an error and bubbles up to the connection object.
dom-idbdatabase-onerror.title: IDBDatabase.onerror

dom-idbdatabase-onversionchange.name: onversionchange
dom-idbdatabase-onversionchange.summary: This example shows an IDBOpenDBRequest.onupgradeneeded block that creates a new object store; it also includes onerror and onabort functions to handle non-success cases, and an onversionchange function to notify when a database structure change has occurred.
dom-idbdatabase-onversionchange.title: IDBDatabase.onversionchange

dom-idbdatabase-version.name: version
dom-idbdatabase-version.summary: An integer containing the version of the connected database.
dom-idbdatabase-version.title: IDBDatabase.version

dom-idbfactory-cmp.name: cmp
dom-idbfactory-cmp.summary: An integer that indicates the result of the comparison; the table below lists the possible values and their meanings:
dom-idbfactory-cmp.title: IDBFactory.cmp()

dom-idbfactory-databases.name: databases
dom-idbfactory-databases.summary: The databases method of the IDBFactory interface returns a list represening all the available databases, including their names and versions.
dom-idbfactory-databases.title: databases

dom-idbfactory-deletedatabase.name: deleteDatabase
dom-idbfactory-deletedatabase.summary: The deleteDatabase() method of the IDBFactory interface requests the deletion of a database. The method returns an IDBOpenDBRequest object immediately, and performs the deletion operation asynchronously.
dom-idbfactory-deletedatabase.title: IDBFactory.deleteDatabase()

dom-idbfactory-open.name: open
dom-idbfactory-open.summary: If an error occurs while the database connection is being opened, then an error event is fired on the request object returned from this method.
dom-idbfactory-open.title: IDBFactory.open()

factory-interface.name: IDBFactory
factory-interface.summary: In the following code snippet, we make a request to open a database, and include handlers for the success and error cases. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
factory-interface.title: IDBFactory

dom-idbindex-count.name: count
dom-idbindex-count.summary: A IDBRequest object on which subsequent events related to this operation are fired.
dom-idbindex-count.title: IDBIndex.count()

dom-idbindex-getall.name: getAll
dom-idbindex-getall.summary: There is a performance cost associated with looking at the value property of a cursor, because the object is created lazily. To use a feature like getAll(), the browser has to create all the objects at once. If you are just interested in looking at each of the keys, for instance, it is more efficient to use a cursor. If you are trying to get an array of all the objects in an object store, though, you should use getAll().
dom-idbindex-getall.title: IDBIndex.getAll()

dom-idbindex-getallkeys.name: getAllKeys
dom-idbindex-getallkeys.summary: An IDBRequest object on which subsequent events related to this operation are fired.
dom-idbindex-getallkeys.title: IDBIndex.getAllKeys()

dom-idbindex-getallkeys.name: getAllKeys
dom-idbindex-getallkeys.summary: An IDBRequest object on which subsequent events related to this operation are fired.
dom-idbindex-getallkeys.title: IDBIndex.getAllKeys()

dom-idbindex-getkey.name: getKey
dom-idbindex-getkey.summary: If a key is found it is set as the result of the request object: this returns the primary key of the record the key is associated with, not the whole record as IDBIndex.get does.
dom-idbindex-getkey.title: IDBIndex.getKey()

dom-idbindex-keypath.name: keyPath
dom-idbindex-keypath.summary: Any data type that can be used as a key path.
dom-idbindex-keypath.title: IDBIndex.keyPath

dom-idbindex-name.name: name
dom-idbindex-name.summary: A DOMString specifying a name for the index.
dom-idbindex-name.title: IDBIndex.name

dom-idbindex-opencursor.name: openCursor
dom-idbindex-opencursor.summary: The method sets the position of the cursor to the appropriate record, based on the specified direction.
dom-idbindex-opencursor.title: IDBIndex.openCursor()

dom-idbindex-openkeycursor.name: openKeyCursor
dom-idbindex-openkeycursor.summary: The method sets the position of the cursor to the appropriate key, based on the specified direction.
dom-idbindex-openkeycursor.title: IDBIndex.openKeyCursor()

index-interface.name: IDBIndex
index-interface.summary: IDBIndex interface of the IndexedDB API provides asynchronous access to an index in a database. An index is a kind of object store for looking up records in another object store, called the referenced object store. You use this interface to retrieve data.
index-interface.title: IDBIndex

dom-idbkeyrange-bound.name: bound
dom-idbkeyrange-bound.summary: IDBKeyRange: The newly created key range.
dom-idbkeyrange-bound.title: IDBKeyRange.bound()

dom-idbkeyrange-includes.name: includes
dom-idbkeyrange-includes.summary: key The key you want to check for in your key range. This can be any type.
dom-idbkeyrange-includes.title: IDBKeyRange.includes()

dom-idbkeyrange-includes.name: includes
dom-idbkeyrange-includes.summary: key The key you want to check for in your key range. This can be any type.
dom-idbkeyrange-includes.title: IDBKeyRange.includes()

dom-idbkeyrange-lower.name: lower
dom-idbkeyrange-lower.summary: The lower bound of the key range (can be any type.)
dom-idbkeyrange-lower.title: IDBKeyRange.lower

dom-idbkeyrange-lowerbound-lower-open-lo.name: lowerBound
dom-idbkeyrange-lowerbound-lower-open-lo.summary: IDBKeyRange: The newly created key range.
dom-idbkeyrange-lowerbound-lower-open-lo.title: IDBKeyRange.lowerBound()

dom-idbkeyrange-only.name: only
dom-idbkeyrange-only.summary: value is the value for the new key range.
dom-idbkeyrange-only.title: IDBKeyRange.only()

dom-idbkeyrange-upper.name: upper
dom-idbkeyrange-upper.summary: The upper bound of the key range (can be any type.)
dom-idbkeyrange-upper.title: IDBKeyRange.upper

dom-idbkeyrange-upperbound-upper-open-up.name: upperBound
dom-idbkeyrange-upperbound-upper-open-up.summary: IDBKeyRange: The newly created key range.
dom-idbkeyrange-upperbound-upper-open-up.title: IDBKeyRange.upperBound()

keyrange.name: IDBKeyRange
keyrange.summary: A key range can be a single value or a range with upper and lower bounds or endpoints. If the key range has both upper and lower bounds, then it is bounded; if it has no bounds, it is unbounded. A bounded key range can either be open (the endpoints are excluded) or closed (the endpoints are included). To retrieve all keys within a certain range, you can use the following code constructs:
keyrange.title: IDBKeyRange

dom-idbobjectstore-add.name: add
dom-idbobjectstore-add.summary: To determine if the add operation has completed successfully, listen for the transactions complete event in addition to the IDBObjectStore.add requests success event, because the transaction may still fail after the success event fires. In other words, the success event is only triggered when the transaction has been successfully queued.
dom-idbobjectstore-add.title: IDBObjectStore.add()

dom-idbobjectstore-clear.name: clear
dom-idbobjectstore-clear.summary: Clearing an object store consists of removing all records from the object store and removing all records in indexes that reference the object store. To remove only some of the records in a store, use IDBObjectStore.delete passing a key or IDBKeyRange.
dom-idbobjectstore-clear.title: IDBObjectStore.clear()

dom-idbobjectstore-count.name: count
dom-idbobjectstore-count.summary: An IDBRequest object on which subsequent events related to this operation are fired.
dom-idbobjectstore-count.title: IDBObjectStore.count()

dom-idbobjectstore-createindex.name: createIndex
dom-idbobjectstore-createindex.summary: Note that this method must be called only from a VersionChange transaction mode callback.
dom-idbobjectstore-createindex.title: IDBObjectStore.createIndex()

dom-idbobjectstore-delete.name: delete
dom-idbobjectstore-delete.summary: An IDBRequest object on which subsequent events related to this operation are fired. The request.result attribute is set to undefined.
dom-idbobjectstore-delete.title: IDBObjectStore.delete()

dom-idbobjectstore-deleteindex.name: deleteIndex
dom-idbobjectstore-deleteindex.summary: Note that this method must be called only from a VersionChange transaction mode callback. Note that this method synchronously modifies the IDBObjectStore.indexNames property.
dom-idbobjectstore-deleteindex.title: IDBObjectStore.deleteIndex()

dom-idbobjectstore-get.name: get
dom-idbobjectstore-get.summary: If a value is successfully found, then a structured clone of it is created and set as the result of the request object.
dom-idbobjectstore-get.title: IDBObjectStore.get()

dom-idbobjectstore-getall.name: getAll
dom-idbobjectstore-getall.summary: If a value is successfully found, then a structured clone of it is created and set as the result of the request object.
dom-idbobjectstore-getall.title: IDBObjectStore.getAll()

dom-idbobjectstore-getallkeys.name: getAllKeys
dom-idbobjectstore-getallkeys.summary: If a value is successfully found, then a structured clone of it is created and set as the result of the request object.
dom-idbobjectstore-getallkeys.title: IDBObjectStore.getAllKeys()

dom-idbobjectstore-getkey.name: getKey
dom-idbobjectstore-getkey.summary: If a key is successfully found, then a structured clone of it is created and set as the result of the request object.
dom-idbobjectstore-getkey.title: IDBObjectStore.getKey()

dom-idbobjectstore-index.name: index
dom-idbobjectstore-index.summary: An IDBIndex object for accessing the index.
dom-idbobjectstore-index.title: IDBObjectStore.index()

dom-idbobjectstore-keypath.name: keyPath
dom-idbobjectstore-keypath.summary: If this property is null, the application must provide a key for each modification operation.
dom-idbobjectstore-keypath.title: IDBObjectStore.keyPath

dom-idbobjectstore-name.name: name
dom-idbobjectstore-name.summary: A DOMString containing the object store's name.
dom-idbobjectstore-name.title: IDBObjectStore.name

dom-idbobjectstore-opencursor.name: openCursor
dom-idbobjectstore-opencursor.summary: To determine if the add operation has completed successfully, listen for the resultss success event.
dom-idbobjectstore-opencursor.title: IDBObjectStore.openCursor()

dom-idbobjectstore-openkeycursor.name: openKeyCursor
dom-idbobjectstore-openkeycursor.summary: To determine if the add operation has completed successfully, listen for the resultss success event.
dom-idbobjectstore-openkeycursor.title: IDBObjectStore.openKeyCursor()

dom-idbobjectstore-put.name: put
dom-idbobjectstore-put.summary: The put method is an update or insert method. See the IDBObjectStore.add method for an insert only method.
dom-idbobjectstore-put.title: IDBObjectStore.put()

object-store-interface.name: IDBObjectStore
object-store-interface.summary: This example shows a variety of different uses of object stores, from updating the data structure with IDBObjectStore.createIndex inside an onupgradeneeded function, to adding a new item to our object store with IDBObjectStore.add. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
object-store-interface.title: IDBObjectStore

dom-idbopendbrequest-onblocked.name: onblocked
dom-idbopendbrequest-onblocked.summary: The onblocked event handler of the IDBOpenDBRequest interface is the event handler for the blocked event. This event is triggered when the upgradeneeded should be triggered because of a version change but the database is still in use (that is, not closed) somewhere, even after the versionchange event was sent.
dom-idbopendbrequest-onblocked.title: IDBOpenDBRequest.onblocked

dom-idbopendbrequest-onupgradeneeded.name: onupgradeneeded
dom-idbopendbrequest-onupgradeneeded.summary: In the following example you can see the onupgradeneeded handler being used to update the database structure if a database with a higher version number is loaded. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
dom-idbopendbrequest-onupgradeneeded.title: IDBOpenDBRequest.onupgradeneeded

idbopendbrequest.name: IDBOpenDBRequest
idbopendbrequest.summary: Also inherits methods from its parents IDBRequest and EventTarget.
idbopendbrequest.title: IDBOpenDBRequest

dom-idbrequest-error.name: error
dom-idbrequest-error.summary: A DOMError containing the relevant error. In Chrome 48+/Firefox 58+ this property returns a DOMException because DOMError has been removed from the DOM standard. The following error codes are returned under certain conditions:
dom-idbrequest-error.title: IDBRequest.error

dom-idbrequest-onerror.summary: The following example requests a given record title, onsuccess gets the associated record from the IDBObjectStore (made available as objectStoreTitleRequest.result), updates one property of the record, and then puts the updated record back into the object store. Also included at the bottom is an onerror function that reports what the error was if the request fails. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
dom-idbrequest-onerror.title: IDBRequest.onerror

dom-idbrequest-onsuccess.name: onsuccess
dom-idbrequest-onsuccess.summary: The following example requests a given record title, onsuccess gets the associated record from the IDBObjectStore (made available as objectStoreTitleRequest.result), updates one property of the record, and then puts the updated record back into the object store. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
dom-idbrequest-onsuccess.title: IDBRequest.onsuccess

dom-idbrequest-readystate.name: readyState
dom-idbrequest-readystate.summary: The IDBRequestReadyState of the request, which takes one of the following two values:
dom-idbrequest-readystate.title: IDBRequest.readyState

dom-idbrequest-source.name: source
dom-idbrequest-source.summary: An object representing the source of the request, such as an IDBIndex, IDBObjectStore or IDBCursor.
dom-idbrequest-source.title: IDBRequest.source

request-api.name: IDBRequest
request-api.summary: The request object does not initially contain any information about the result of the operation, but once information becomes available, an event is fired on the request, and the information becomes available through the properties of the IDBRequest instance.
request-api.title: IDBRequest

dom-idbtransaction-abort.name: abort
dom-idbtransaction-abort.summary: The abort() method of the IDBTransaction interface rolls back all the changes to objects in the database associated with this transaction.
dom-idbtransaction-abort.title: IDBTransaction.abort()

dom-idbtransaction-commit.name: commit
dom-idbtransaction-commit.summary: The commit() method of the IDBTransaction interface commits the transaction if it is called on an active transaction.
dom-idbtransaction-commit.title: IDBTransaction.commit()

dom-idbtransaction-error.name: error
dom-idbtransaction-error.summary: A DOMError containing the relevant error. In Chrome 48+/Firefox 58+ this property returns a DOMException because DOMError has been removed from the DOM standard. The exact error is one of serveral possibilities. It can be a reference to the same error as the request object that raised it, or a transaction failure (for example QuotaExceededError or UnknownError).
dom-idbtransaction-error.title: IDBTransaction.error

dom-idbtransaction-mode.name: mode
dom-idbtransaction-mode.summary: An IDBTransactionMode object defining the mode for isolating access to data in the current object stores:
dom-idbtransaction-mode.title: IDBTransaction.mode

dom-idbtransaction-objectstore.name: objectStore
dom-idbtransaction-objectstore.summary: The objectStore() method of the IDBTransaction interface returns an object store that has already been added to the scope of this transaction.
dom-idbtransaction-objectstore.title: IDBTransaction.objectStore()

dom-idbtransaction-objectstorenames.name: objectStoreNames
dom-idbtransaction-objectstorenames.summary: The objectStoreNames read-only property of the IDBTransaction interface returns a DOMStringList of names of IDBObjectStore objects.
dom-idbtransaction-objectstorenames.title: IDBTransaction.objectStoreNames

dom-idbtransaction-onabort.name: onabort
dom-idbtransaction-onabort.summary: In the following code snippet, we open a read/write transaction on our database and add some data to an object store. Note also the functions attached to transaction event handlers to report on the outcome of the transaction opening in the event of success or failure. Note the transaction.onabort = function(event) { }; block, reporting when the transaction has been aborted. For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live.)
dom-idbtransaction-onabort.title: IDBTransaction.onabort

dom-idbtransaction-oncomplete.name: oncomplete
dom-idbtransaction-oncomplete.summary: The oncomplete event handler of the IDBTransaction interface handles the complete event, fired when the transaction successfully completes.
dom-idbtransaction-oncomplete.title: IDBTransaction.oncomplete

dom-idbtransaction-onerror.name: onerror
dom-idbtransaction-onerror.summary: The onerror event handler of the IDBTransaction interface handles the error event, fired when a request returns an error and bubbles up to the transaction object.
dom-idbtransaction-onerror.title: IDBTransaction.onerror

transaction.name: IDBTransaction
transaction.summary: The IDBTransaction interface of the IndexedDB API provides a static, asynchronous transaction on a database using event handler attributes. All reading and writing of data is done within transactions. You use IDBDatabase to start transactions, IDBTransaction to set the mode of the transaction (e.g. is it readonly or readwrite), and you access an IDBObjectStore to make a request. You can also use an IDBTransaction object to abort transactions.
transaction.title: IDBTransaction

dom-idbversionchangeevent-oldversion.name: oldVersion
dom-idbversionchangeevent-oldversion.summary: The oldVersion read-only property of the IDBVersionChangeEvent interface returns the old version number of the database.
dom-idbversionchangeevent-oldversion.title: IDBVersionChangeEvent.oldVersion

idbversionchangeevent.name: IDBVersionChangeEvent
idbversionchangeevent.summary: The IDBVersionChangeEvent interface of the IndexedDB API indicates that the version of the database has changed, as the result of an IDBOpenDBRequest.onupgradeneeded event handler function.
idbversionchangeevent.title: IDBVersionChangeEvent

dom-windoworworkerglobalscope-indexeddb.name: indexedDB
dom-windoworworkerglobalscope-indexeddb.summary: The indexedDB read-only property of the WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope mixin provides a mechanism for applications to asynchronously access the capabilities of indexed databases.
dom-windoworworkerglobalscope-indexeddb.title: WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope.indexedDB
